        "id": "ca97302c-12da-460c-bf9e-a13b0de8ed41",
        "score": 0.72758734,
        "text": "The document page is from the CAISO BPM for Market Operations, focusing on Ancillary Services (AS). It outlines:\n\n- **Content Overview**: Describes AS regions, CAISO's determination and procurement of AS, calculation of AS marginal prices, other considerations, and certification/testing requirements.\n\n- **Ancillary Services Regions**: These are network partitions imposing regional constraints on AS procurement. Defined by PNodes, they ensure reliability and manage transmission limitations. Constraints include minimum AS procurement and maximum targets to ensure deliverability.\n\n- **Regional Constraints**: Address transmission limitations and ensure AS can cover outages and regional constraints. They reflect system topology and deliverability needs.\n\n- **Region Definition**: At least two AS regions with non-zero procurement limits exist. The \"Expanded System Region\" includes the entire CAISO Balancing Authority Area and all system resources at scheduling points outside this area. Requirements for AS types are detailed in the BPM for Market Instruments.\n\nThe document emphasizes the structured approach to managing AS to maintain system reliability and efficiency.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Operations/page_171.jpg",
          "page_num": 171,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Operations",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "4213cf65-397a-4b04-a5ea-93eb9682323a",
        "score": 0.7275378,
        "text": "The document outlines guidelines for submitting bids for Ancillary Services (AS) in the California Independent System Operator (CAISO) market. Key points include:\n\n1. **Eligibility**: Certified Participating Loads and Proxy Demand Resources can provide Non-Spinning Reserve only.\n\n2. **Resource Capacity**: The same capacity can be offered for multiple Ancillary Services simultaneously. Scheduling Coordinators (SCs) can submit bids for Spinning or Non-Spinning Reserve from certified resources.\n\n3. **Invalid Bids**: SCs are notified promptly if a bid is invalid.\n\n4. **Tariff Appendix II**: For resources under this tariff, bids must be priced at $0/MWh, or a Submission for Self-Provision can be made.\n\n5. **Market Operations**: CAISO operates a competitive Day-Ahead Market (DAM), Hour-Ahead Scheduling Process (HASP), and Real-Time Market (RTM) for procuring AS. Bids for the DAM must be submitted at least seven days before the trading day.\n\n6. **Must Offer Obligation (MOO)**: Bids for DAM AS with MOO are enforced by SIBR rules. Limited resources like hydro units are not subject to AS MOO.\n\n7. **SIBR Rules**: If no AS component exists in a bid, the capacity must match the highest available registered capacity. The Contingency Dispatch Indicator is set to \"Yes\" if an AS component is needed.\n\n8. **RTM Bids**: Submitted incrementally from DAM AS Awards, which are binding and cannot be reduced in RTM. SCs must honor DAM AS Awards when submitting RTM bids.\n\nThe document provides detailed procedural and regulatory information for market participants involved in bidding for Ancillary Services within the CAISO framework.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Instruments/page_98.jpg",
          "page_num": 98,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Instruments",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "b91f2d81-4cae-4ff0-8ed0-6d334d095886",
        "score": 0.7189089,
        "text": "The document page is from the Department of Market Monitoring for California ISO, dated July 2022. It includes Figure 5.4, which shows the hourly average day-ahead regulation requirements for 2021. The graph displays two lines: \"Regulation down\" and \"Regulation up,\" with the y-axis representing hourly average reserve requirements in megawatts (MW) and the x-axis representing hours of the day. \n\nThe text below the graph discusses ancillary service procurement by fuel type from 2019 to 2021. It explains that ancillary service requirements are fulfilled by both internal resources and imports, with limitations set by minimum requirements within the CAISO system. Ancillary services that bid across interties must compete for transmission capacity with energy. Most requirements are met by California ISO resources.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2021/page_186.jpg",
          "page_num": 186,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "957081ad-360f-4884-8d56-b05d1cb1fa2d",
        "score": 0.7122509,
        "text": "The document outlines specific guidelines and requirements related to the California Independent System Operator (CAISO) markets, focusing on Ancillary Services (AS) and reserves. Key points include:\n\n1. **Real-Time Dispatch**: Multi-Stage Generating Resources use rounded transition times from RTUC.\n\n2. **Export Bids**: Exporting AS bids is not supported in CAISO markets, and on-demand obligations are manually supported but not from DAM or RTM.\n\n3. **Reserves Classification**: Spinning and Non-Spinning Reserves in RTM are classified as Contingency Only. DA reserves are reclassified if additional reserves are awarded in RTM. Non-Dynamic System Resources are also considered contingency only.\n\n4. **Dispatching AS**: Contingency Only AS is not typically dispatched as energy in normal RTED mode. In RTCD mode, energy behind both Contingency Only and non-Contingency Only AS is dispatched economically.\n\n5. **Special Circumstances**: Contingency Only Reserves can be dispatched by RTED under specific conditions outlined in CAISO tariff sections.\n\n6. **Energy Bids**: Scheduling Coordinators must submit Energy Bids for Non-Dynamic System Resources with AS bids in RTM. CAISO uses only the AS Bid for optimization, not the associated Energy Bids unless no AS is awarded.\n\n7. **Certification and Testing**: The section references CAISO Tariff Section 8.3.4 and 8.4 for certification and technical requirements for providing AS.\n\nThe document emphasizes the procedural and regulatory framework for managing AS and reserves within CAISO markets.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Operations/page_210.jpg",
          "page_num": 210,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Operations",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "dbaecd0b-6576-4ddc-853a-606dc1cf98ab",
        "score": 0.7095621,
        "text": "The document page outlines processes related to the California Independent System Operator (CAISO) market operations. Key points include:\n\n- **Bidding Rules**: Business rules are applied to generate Day-Ahead Market (DAM) and Real-Time Market (RTM) bids for resources under Resource Adequacy requirements. This includes handling bids for resources with Day-Ahead Ancillary Services or Reliability Unit Commitment (RUC) Awards.\n\n- **Information and Reporting**: Scheduling Coordinators (SCs) receive information about bid validation, modification, and generation. Final bids are forwarded to the CAISO Market, and short-term data storage and reporting are provided.\n\n- **CAISO Market Results Interface (CMRI)**: Accessible through the CAISO portal, it allows SCs to retrieve proprietary market results, such as DAM Energy Schedules, Ancillary Services Awards, and RUC Awards. It supports various reporting functions.\n\n- **Master File (MF)**: Used by CAISO to store business and operational data of market participants, facilitating scheduling and settlement transactions.\n\n- **Automated Dispatch System (ADS)**: Communicates real-time commitment and dispatch instructions to SCs, providing real-time awards.\n\n- **Outage Management**: The system application is used for managing outage-related requests, updates, approvals, and rejections.\n\nThe document references additional sections for detailed information on specific topics like energy bids, ancillary services bids, and reporting information.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Instruments/page_32.jpg",
          "page_num": 32,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Instruments",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "17583ee1-297b-4b51-aeb5-f7ff69095e76",
        "score": 0.70934683,
        "text": "The document outlines the process and requirements for changes in Ancillary Services (AS) regions by the California Independent System Operator (CAISO).\n\n**4.1.2 Ancillary Services Region Change Process:**\n- CAISO evaluates technical factors to adjust or create AS regions, considering operational reliability, load growth, new or retiring resources, transmission changes, and outages.\n- A market impact analysis is conducted to assess potential market power issues.\n- Proposed changes are submitted to stakeholders for comments on market mitigation measures.\n- After stakeholder feedback, CAISO may revise the proposal and submit it to the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) as a Tariff Amendment.\n\n**4.2 Ancillary Services Requirements:**\n- AS requirements are set by CAISO following WECC and NERC standards.\n- AS is procured regionally, not competing within the CAISO Balancing Authority Area.\n- CAISO sets procurement limits to ensure local reliability.\n- Minimum AS requirements consider load and generation path deratings, total transfer capability, and the largest single contingency.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Operations/page_175.jpg",
          "page_num": 175,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Operations",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "46e472c8-5563-451b-b55f-c1b2ca0c2dfe",
        "score": 0.70582485,
        "text": "The document page is from the \"2022 Annual Report on Market Issues and Performance\" by the Department of Market Monitoring, California ISO, dated July 2023. It includes Figure 4.4, which illustrates the hourly average day-ahead regulation requirements for 2022, comparing regulation up and down for 2021 and 2022. The graph shows that regulation requirements fluctuate throughout the day, with peaks and troughs in demand.\n\nThe text discusses ancillary service procurement by fuel type from 2020 to 2022. It explains that ancillary service requirements are fulfilled by both internal resources and imports, with minimum procurement requirements set within the CAISO system. Ancillary services that bid across interties must compete for transmission capacity with energy. Most requirements are met by California ISO resources.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2022/page_159.jpg",
          "page_num": 159,
          "title": "2022 Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "9944cb94-1240-46d6-acbb-1036ef9b6829",
        "score": 0.69709074,
        "text": "The document outlines the process for Scheduling Coordinators (SCs) to trade financial obligations for Ancillary Services (AS) through Inter-SC Trades. These trades involve transferring AS quantities between SCs for specific hours and types, but do not include the obligation to provide the services. The California Independent System Operator (CAISO) charges a system-wide rate for each AS, and SCs settle these obligations independently of market types. \n\nThere are four types of AS that can be traded: Regulation Up, Regulation Down, Spinning Reserve, and Non-Spinning Reserve. SCs can submit Ancillary Services Trades (ASTs) starting at midnight the day before the trading hour, up to 45 minutes prior. The Real-Time Market (RTM) Inter-SC Trade Period involves continuous submission and screening of ASTs by CAISO, which provides feedback on their validity. SCs must provide specific information when submitting an AST.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Instruments/page_133.jpg",
          "page_num": 133,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Instruments",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "f33565a8-e509-4047-ada4-95f245035788",
        "score": 0.6889808,
        "text": "The document page is a table of contents for a manual related to CAISO (California Independent System Operator) Business Practice Manuals. It includes:\n\n1. **Introduction**\n   - Purpose of CAISO Business Practice Manuals\n   - Purpose of this specific manual\n   - References\n\n2. **Market Operations Overview**\n   - **Market Entities**\n     - CAISO\n     - Scheduling Coordinators\n     - Participating Generators\n     - Constrained Output Generator\n     - Multi-Stage Generating Resources\n     - Participating Loads\n     - Non-Participating Loads\n     - Utility Distribution Companies\n     - Metered Subsystems\n     - Balancing Authority Areas\n     - Participating Transmission Owners\n     - System Resource\n     - Non-Generator Resources\n     - Pseudo-Tie\n     - Use-Limited Resources\n     - Conditionally Available Resource\n     - Non-Dispatchable Resource\n     - Run-of-River Hydro\n     - Co-Located Resources\n     - High Sustainable Limit (HSL)\n     - Hybrid Resources\n     - Master and Subordinate aggregate capability constraints (ACCs)\n\n   - **Products & Services**\n     - Energy\n     - Ancillary Services\n\nThe document was last revised on December 23, 2024, and is on page 20.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Operations/page_20.jpg",
          "page_num": 20,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Operations",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "3bcd3c77-198d-4b53-a8ab-59647eaddd42",
        "score": 0.6868486,
        "text": "The document page is from the Department of Market Monitoring \u2013 California ISO, dated June 2020. It includes Figure 6.2, which shows the total ancillary service cost by quarter and type from 2017 to 2019. The services are categorized into regulation down, regulation up, spinning reserves, and non-spinning reserves, with costs displayed in millions of dollars and cost per MWh of load served.\n\nSection 6.2 discusses ancillary service requirements and procurement. The ISO procures four ancillary services in day-ahead and real-time markets: regulation up, regulation down, spinning reserves, and non-spinning reserves. These services must meet Western Electricity Coordinating Council and North American Electric Reliability Corporation standards. The ISO aims to procure all services in the day-ahead market as much as possible.\n\nAncillary services are procured from various regions, including the internal system region, expanded system region, four internal sub-regions, and four expanded sub-regions. These regions have minimum requirements for procurement, and imports are limited by these requirements. Six regions are typically utilized: expanded system, internal system, expanded South of Path 26, internal South of Path 26, expanded North of Path 26, and internal North of Path 26. A footnote mentions a performance payment added in June 2013, referred to as mileage, for regulation up and down markets.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2019/page_179.jpg",
          "page_num": 179,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": "2019",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

