        "score": 0.72663444,
        "text": "The document outlines the certification and testing requirements for Generating Units, System Units, and Load and Proxy Demand Resources (PDRs) under the CAISO Tariff. These entities must comply with CAISO's standards as detailed in the BPM for Compliance Monitoring to submit bids or self-provision Ancillary Services (AS). RDRR and PDR-LSR consumption resources are prohibited from providing AS.\n\nCAISO certifies Multi-Stage Generating Resources for AS at the MSG Configuration level and retains the right to inspect these resources to ensure ongoing compliance with technical requirements. If standards are not met, CAISO may withdraw certification.\n\nThe document specifies that AS certification and capacity are recorded in the Master File after successful testing. Regulation Certification and Testing Requirements are based on CAISO Tariff Section 8.3.4. Units must be certified and tested by CAISO, following specific processes. Units with Automatic Generation Control can be certified for Regulation Up and Down, limited by their 10-minute Ramping capability.\n\nA resource may lose its ability to provide Regulation if its performance falls below a minimum threshold. The ISO provides data to help Scheduling Coordinators monitor performance accuracy, using a weighted average of fifteen-minute intervals.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Operations/page_211.jpg",
          "page_num": 211,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Operations",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "70cb8c86-c8c9-465e-9105-8472b2928d5e",
        "score": 0.6636687,
        "text": "The document outlines the operational requirements for generating units providing Automatic Generation Control (AGC) to the California Independent System Operator (CAISO). It specifies the necessary DNP3 and telemetry data points for real-time visibility, including analog and digital input values to CAISO, and analog output (Set Points) from CAISO. Additionally, it lists telemetry data points such as Unit Control Switch, Unit Authority Switch, Automatic Generation Control, and various operating limits. The document emphasizes that these data points are essential for maintaining grid reliability and that CAISO may require additional telemetry values as needed. It also describes the option for a bumpless transfer method for AGC control, allowing real-time devices to track Set Points when resources are off AGC control.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Direct_Telemetry/page_100.jpg",
          "page_num": 100,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Direct Telemetry",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "3f80497d-1fcb-45bb-99fd-2487f6278527",
        "score": 0.6574818,
        "text": "The document page from California ISO outlines various testing procedures for Generating Units and System Resources:\n\n1. **Regulation Testing (4.3.3):** \n   - Tests the ability of a Generating Unit or System Resource to adjust its output over its full Regulation capacity within a 10-minute period using the CAISO EMS.\n\n2. **Voltage Support Testing (4.3.4):**\n   - Monitors a Generating Unit's response to Voltage Support instructions to ensure compliance with Dispatch Instructions.\n   - **Testing of Generating Unit:** Involves unannounced Dispatch Instructions to adjust the power factor within specified limits.\n   - **Testing of Other Reactive Devices:** Involves unannounced Dispatch Instructions for devices like shunt capacitors and static var compensators.\n\n3. **Black Start Testing (4.3.5):**\n   - Tests the Black Start capability by issuing unannounced instructions to start and synchronize the Generating Unit, including testing communication circuits and simulating necessary switching.\n   - Measures compliance with Black Start contract terms, with payment based on the contract price for output.\n\n4. **RUC Capacity Testing (4.3.6):**\n   - Tests the capability of various resources to provide RUC Capacity through unannounced Dispatch Instructions.\n   - Instructions may require resources to come online and ramp up as needed.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Compliance_Monitoring/page_14.jpg",
          "page_num": 14,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Compliance Monitoring",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "354a5384-37cb-4fdf-b5b2-e69268660813",
        "score": 0.6551725,
        "text": "The document page is from the ISO Business Practice Manual, specifically focusing on BPM for Direct Telemetry. It outlines procedures and definitions related to the control and monitoring of power generation resources.\n\n1. **Unit Automatic Switch (UASW):**\n   - **Purpose:** When UASW is on (High), the resource is available only for CAISO AGC Set Point.\n   - **Method:** UASW can be a hardware or software switch accessible to the resource operator.\n\n2. **Unit Automatic Generation Control (UAGC):**\n   - **Definition:** Indicates readiness for CAISO to send AGC Set Points. Requires AGC certification for market participation.\n   - **Purpose:** Used for Settlement to ensure the resource meets scheduled generation expectations. When on (High), CAISO can send MW Set Points.\n   - **Method:** UAGC status is a digital \"AND\" calculation of UCON, UCTL, and UASW points.\n\n3. **Automatic Voltage Regulator (AVR) / Power System Stabilizer (PSS) Status:**\n   - **Definition:** AVR controls terminal voltage automatically (ON/OFF). PSS works with AVR for frequency excursions (In/Out of service).\n   - **Purpose:** Required for system reliability assessment and stability simulations. Necessary for all Generating Units under WECC requirements.\n\nThe document emphasizes the importance of these controls for maintaining system reliability and compliance with regulatory standards.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Direct_Telemetry/page_127.jpg",
          "page_num": 127,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Direct Telemetry",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "c611d76d-c219-48d0-aaa9-e7379a868682",
        "score": 0.6438651,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures and requirements for Real and Reactive Power Capability tests for generators. Key points include:\n\n1. **Test Plan Submission**: Generator owners must submit a test plan detailing the time, duration, and target MW/MVAR outputs for each test step.\n\n2. **Voltage Regulation**: If voltage limits are approached during tests, the generator owner must notify the PTO to adjust system voltage using available equipment.\n\n3. **Coordination**: Generators must coordinate voltage regulating systems with their capabilities, including providing descriptions of control systems and ensuring models align with power flow and dynamic models.\n\n4. **Frequency and Voltage Relay Settings**: Generators with protective relays must provide relay settings to CAISO and PTO, ensuring compliance with NERC reliability standards.\n\n5. **Electromagnetic Transient Model (EMT)**: All asynchronous generating units must submit EMT models. Synchronous units must submit models for specific studies. CAISO and PTOs will request these models, with a 12-month submission timeline from the request date. Requirements are detailed in specific sections and on the CAISO website.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Transmission_Planning_Process/page_86.jpg",
          "page_num": 86,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Transmission Planning Process",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "77471e95-b5a3-414c-80e5-0246c0d1a167",
        "score": 0.63916886,
        "text": "The document is from the California Independent System Operator Corporation and pertains to the Fifth Replacement Electronic Tariff. It outlines certification requirements for Multi-Stage Generating (MSG) Resources as per Section 8, Appendix K of the CAISO Tariff and Business Practice Manuals. These requirements apply to MSG configurations certified for providing Ancillary Services to CAISO Markets.\n\nKey points include:\n\n- Scheduling Coordinators must submit Ancillary Services Bids for certified MSG configurations.\n- Specific operating characteristics must be submitted for certification.\n- Requirements include standards for control, capability, and availability.\n- Operating characteristics involve ramp rate changes, power factor, maximum and minimum output, immediate response capability, and availability duration.\n- Appendix K and Business Practice Manuals differentiate operating characteristics for Ancillary Services.\n- Regulation resources must be controllable and monitored by CAISO's EMS using standard communication and control systems.\n\nThe document is dated August 3, 2024, and is part of Section 8.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Fifth_Replacement_FERC_Electric_Tariff/page_164.jpg",
          "page_num": 164,
          "title": "Fifth Replacement FERC Electric Tariff",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "f04afd46-b9f4-4807-b83e-3eb3b999fe10",
        "score": 0.63389575,
        "text": "The document is part of the California Independent System Operator Corporation's Fifth Replacement Tariff, specifically Appendix K, which outlines the Ancillary Service Requirements Protocol (ASRP). It focuses on the certification for regulation of Ancillary Service Providers.\n\n### Key Points:\n\n1. **Certification Requirements**:\n   - Ancillary Service Providers must meet specific operating characteristics and technical requirements to provide regulation services, either through a CAISO award or self-provision.\n   - Providers must be certified by CAISO unless temporarily exempted.\n\n2. **Operating Characteristics**:\n   - **Capacity**: The resource must have a rated capacity of at least 500 KW, unless part of an approved aggregation or a storage/Distributed Energy Resource Aggregation of 100 KW or greater.\n   - **Regulation Timing**: Maximum regulation must be reached within 10 minutes.\n   - **Response Capability**: The resource must adjust power levels in response to CAISO's EMS control signals.\n   - **Dispatchability**: Resources must be dispatchable continuously for at least 60 minutes in the Day Ahead Market and 30 minutes in the Real Time Market.\n   - **Accuracy**: The resource's response accuracy to CAISO's EMS signal must exceed 25%.\n\n3. **Technical Requirements**:\n   - **Control**: \n     - A direct, digital control signal from CAISO EMS must meet minimum performance standards.\n     - The resource's response to control signals must also meet these standards, which will be developed and posted by CAISO.\n\nThe document sets forth the criteria and standards necessary for providers to participate in CAISO's regulation services, ensuring reliability and efficiency in energy management.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Fifth_Replacement_FERC_Electric_Tariff/page_1890.jpg",
          "page_num": 1890,
          "title": "Fifth Replacement FERC Electric Tariff",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "ecba0f36-21f7-4e32-a361-d406400d13b5",
        "score": 0.6242237,
        "text": "The document outlines the process and fees associated with technological advancement assessments conducted by the California Independent System Operator (CAISO) and Participating Transmission Owners (TOs). The assessment fee is $2,500, split equally between CAISO and the Participating TOs, covering costs incurred by CAISO, TOs, or third parties. The assessments are directed by CAISO, with Participating TOs or third parties performing parts of the work as agreed. CAISO must complete assessments within 30 days, and any third-party work must adhere to the same timeline. Interconnection Customers must follow specific submission guidelines, including email subject line requirements, when requesting assessments. The document references additional sections for detailed procedural and analytical requirements.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_For_Generator_Management/page_84.jpg",
          "page_num": 84,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual For Generator Management",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "dc18488f-04bc-422e-947a-3a34d8816656",
        "score": 0.61388814,
        "text": "The document outlines requirements for non-synchronous generators to maintain composite power delivery at continuous rated power output. These generators can meet dynamic reactive power needs using inverters, dynamic reactive power devices (like Static VAR Compensators), and static reactive power devices (like capacitors).\n\nThe Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) accepted the California Independent System Operator (CAISO) compliance filing, applicable to:\n\n- Existing asynchronous generating facilities upgrading units after September 21, 2016.\n- Facilities requesting a re-study under specific CAISO tariff sections after September 21, 2016.\n- Interconnection customers posting financial security for asynchronous facilities after September 21, 2016.\n- Customers submitting interconnection requests for asynchronous facilities under the Fast Track process after September 21, 2016.\n\nFor synchronous generators, requirements remain unchanged, requiring a power factor between 0.95 leading to 0.90 lagging. A white paper published on February 25, 2019, provides guidelines for evaluating the reactive capabilities of asynchronous generators, ensuring a consistent approach among CAISO and Participating Transmission Owners (PTOs).\n\nThe guidelines allow PTOs to deviate from procedures if general principles are followed, such as using automated control schemes to meet reactive power requirements if a generator is deficient under extreme conditions.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_For_Generator_Interconnection_and_Deliverability_Allocation_Procedures_(GIDAP)_BPM/page_47.jpg",
          "page_num": 47,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual For Generator Interconnection and Deliverability Allocation Procedures (GIDAP) BPM",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "8d56c8ce-ddd2-4cd1-9308-1bb3c219018f",
        "score": 0.6134013,
        "text": "The document is from the CAISO Business Practice Manual, specifically focusing on Scheduling Coordinator Customer Information. It outlines the requirements for a Scheduling Coordinator Applicant to certify their authority to represent Generators and Loads as Scheduling Coordinator Customers. Key points include:\n\n1. **Certification Requirements**:\n   - Generators must have agreements with CAISO as per specific appendices.\n   - UDCs (Utility Distribution Companies) must have operating agreements with CAISO.\n   - CAISO Metered Entities need meter service agreements with CAISO.\n   - Wholesale Customers must be eligible for wholesale transmission service.\n   - End-Use Customers must be eligible for service as Direct Access End Users under approved programs.\n\n2. **Convergence Bidding Entities**:\n   - Applicants must certify their authority to represent these entities and submit bids on their behalf.\n\n3. **Additional Information**:\n   - Further details are provided in Attachment C, relevant to the selections in this section.\n\nThe document is part of Version 14, last revised on August 27, 2024.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Scheduling_Coordinator_Application_Form/page_3.jpg",
          "page_num": 3,
          "title": "Scheduling Coordinator Application Form",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

